    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_386465">Hes kind of stuck. He wants to compete with WoW... but WoW is an AGP era game, very AGP compatible, and I am going to guess over two thirds of its players are sporting an AGP card.  I would be shocked if it was under half.<br />
<br />
I kind of blame the game industry for not enough straight talk here.  They all like to be a little grey with what a min system is in development.  They dont like to come out and say &quot;your ps2... this is ps3 software&quot;  because everyone wants ps2 customers  <br />
<br />
Now when it comes to agp versus pci express and related various bus improvements there have been games that have been able to straddle both with some graphical success.  For example, I know Oblivion gives AGP card users a very fulfilling and solid graphical experience without turning it into stick figures (IE you can use HDR or BLOOM at a 1024 resolution) while at the same time giving some graphical settings that reward more modern bus architectures.  Lets call them ps2.5 compatible in my analogy.  Really they are true ps2 and ps3 hybrid releases.  <br />
<br />
Little bit of straight talk from here there basically said Vanguard is all ps3 and isnt really a ps2 game (in my analogy).  IE he said it just isnt going to work for an AGP user.<br />
<br />
But wow is AGP era game.  And it appears that Middle Earth online is a pretty successful hybrid game.  So he is going to be competing with one AGP era game and a game that successfully offers a compelling graphical experience to AGP users with new cards with a game that he reports offers AGP users buttkiss until they upgrade.  I have no idea if its true, but thats sure the way he makes it read.  So GL with that.  From where I sit I have alot of friends including myself that are looking to give away 15 dollars a month, but arnt seeing PCIExpress in their near future.  And I suspect that wow has a number of people that fit the same description.<br />
<br />
To me though it screams of mismanagement when he reports that on AGP system his game is not GPU bound.  To everyone else they read &quot;not gpu bound&quot; and see good.  I see bad.  The reason I see bad is because when the name of the game is to provide the richest graphical experience on the system consumer owns versus the system you want them to own left over resources on a brand new card purchases means you got caught sleeping.  <br />
<br />
I mean a WoW user goes out and buys a 7950GT on an AGP 8x slot and looks to use that power in game because WoW doesnt really do it, and your response is he is going to have alot of left over GPU power and going to bottlenecked by his bus then that is on the developer making a bad prediction.  Programming graphics is a bit of an art.  Its alot of slgiht of hand making &quot;cool graphics&quot;.  I can promise you this:  the MMORPG fully utilizing that 7800GS/7900GS/7950GT even on a AGP slot has an automatic edge when it comes to getting consumers.  [Here fully utilizing means providing a state of the art experience for the user that they wouldnt have had with a 6800 as opposed to just chopping framerate, cuasing the GPU to smoke, and saying &quot;see still not enough&quot; ]<br />
<br />
And to be honest it sounds like middle earth nailed this in a way vanguard did not.  Right now he is holding onto a fantasy that his ps2 users will upgrade to ps3 while simultaneously I expect a little work on the back end to try to get it to be a little more ps2 friendly since his main competitors are both way ahead of him in that department. [on the plus side Vanguard is lightyears ahead of WoW in offering you a graphical experience that utilizes your new pci express rig. ]<br />
<br />
End of analogy.  I know why the analogy right?  Its to show we put a great deal of effort into the topic of compatibility in other context.  But when it comes to this great leap forward in system bus speed as it relates to gameplay the entire industry has been a bit quie.  We got people with &quot;nearly no compability&quot; pretending in development to be the games that actually bridged the gap when they know darn well they arnt.  The lack of education in the average consumer is starting to create a little backlash. <br />
<br />
So call new agp cards versus pciexpress etc what it is:  an issue of compability. And decide if your going to be next generation or if your going to be center mass which is old generation or decide if your going to gimp the capabilities of your game to stay old generation compatible (oblivion again).  But decide and advertise it and stop praying stupid consumers will be good business.<br />
<br />
<br />
Its not like old generation games are all that fugly.  I mean oblivion is a pretty sexy game.  I mean the AGP gpus are still pretty strong.  They have alot of rendering effects to offer just not as much texturing etc.  And for the love of god use these new GPUs even if the system underlying them dont offer you the bandwidth you really want!<br />
<br />
It prolly didnt do Vanguard any favors at all when these companies started releasing new GPUs on the AGP slot because it created an area of competition in which Vanguard was just not ready to offer a compelling experience.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
