    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_386572">I think Gnippins has touched on a few relevant points.  Users don't like inconvenience.  Losing the chat server (the most important player to player interaction point of a MMORPG) on any sort of regular basis is guaranteed to make your users quit.  Look at Asheron's Call 2.<br />
<br />
The lack of end game content and/or meaningful PvP means you've just alienated your hardcore users.  They'll burn through the content and quit.  End gamers aren't the majority of the players but they do provide the majority of the buzz and news about MMORPGs.  Not having the hardcore content for newsworthy events like server or world firsts, in addition to epic style loot news, really cuts down on how much people talk about a game.<br />
<br />
That isn't the only set of problems though.  The game's performance is pretty horrible.  I run an E6600 with 2GB of ram and a pair of 6800GTs in SLI on a 1280x1024 panel.  In some areas the game runs just fine.  In others it chugs, is choppy, and damned near unplayable.  No other game I own, online or offline, performs as poorly as Vanguard.<br />
<br />
In my opinion Brad and team are still living in their dream world from the original EQ days.  Vanguard is a game built for a market that isn't nearly as large as they think it is.  I find many similarities between the stated goals of Vanguard and Shadowbane in terms of catering to the hardcore.<br />
<br />
I also see a parallel between Vanguard and Shadowbane in their bugginess.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
